Ayala, Cheung Kong, PCCW, PT Inco: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-08-14T22:01:17Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-14/ayala-cheung-kong-pccw-pt-inco-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Ayala Corp. (AC)  : The owner of the largest Philippine
developer and the nation’s third-biggest bank by assets posted a
12 percent gain in first-half profit to 4.9 billion pesos ($115
million), the Manila-based company said in a statement. The
stock increased 1 percent to 308.20 pesos.  Cheung Kong  (Holdings) Ltd. (1 HK): Chairman Li Ka-Shing
bought 258,000 shares of the company at an average price of
HK$107.985 each on Aug. 10, according to a disclosure filing to
the  Hong Kong  stock exchange. Cheung Kong, which develops and
invests in real estates, retreated 0.8 percent to HK$105.40.  China Mobile Ltd. (941)  (941 HK): The world’s biggest phone
carrier by subscribers and its controlling shareholder China
Mobile Communications Corp. agreed to set up a finance company
with a registered capital of 5 billion yuan ($782 million),
according to a statement to the Hong Kong stock exchange. China
Mobile slipped 0.1 percent to HK$73.95.  PCCW Ltd. (8)  (8 HK): Hong Kong’s biggest telephone company
posted first-half net income of HK$824 million ($106 million), a
gain of 8 percent from a year earlier, according to a statement
to the Hong Kong stock exchange. That compares with the median
HK$810 million estimate of three analysts in a Bloomberg News
survey. PCCW rose 2.3 percent to HK$3.07.  Powerchip Technology Corp. (5346)  (5346 TT): The chip maker
received agreement from creditor banks to extend medium- to
long-term credit by six months and debt repayments by the same
period, the Taiwan-based company said in a statement to a local
stock exchange on Aug. 12. The stock fell 1.7 percent to NT$2.98.  PT International Nickel  Indonesia  (INCO IJ): The company’s
President Director Tony Wenas has tendered his resignation
because of “personal and family reasons,” the Indonesian
producer of the metal said in a statement to the stock exchange.
PT Inco, as the company is also known, will propose a new
president at a shareholders meeting in September, it said. PT
Inco climbed 2.7 percent to 3,800 rupiah.  Robinsons Land Corp. (RLC)  : The Philippine builder of
apartments, offices and malls said net income in the third
quarter of its fiscal year 2011 rose to 1.01 billion pesos from
792.5 million pesos a year earlier. Robinson rose 0.5 percent to
12.28 pesos.  San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  : The Philippine’s biggest food
and drinks company posted a 72 percent increase in first-half
net income to 10.8 billion pesos, a stock-exchange filing showed.
The company also said it will sell 59.09 million Manila Electric
Co. (MER PM) shares to unit  San Miguel  Pure Foods Co. at 220
pesos each. San Miguel rose 1.6 percent to 120.90 pesos. Manila
Electric decreased 3.8 percent to 257 pesos.  Taishin Financial Holding Co. (2887 TT): The financial
services company’s President Lin Keh-hsiao fell to his death in
a mountain climbing accident, the company said in a statement to
the Taiwan stock exchange on Aug. 12. The board will convene to
decide his replacement, it said, without giving a timetable. The
stock was flat at NT$13.65.  Tung Ho Steel Enterprise Corp. (2006)  (2006 TT): The Taipei-based
steel maker was raised to “add” from “neutral” at Fubon
Securities Co. by equity analyst Kevin Lin. The six-month share-
price estimate is NT$36.80. The stock dropped 2.6 percent to
NT$30.60.  SP Setia Bhd. (SPSB)  : The Malaysian property developer
agreed to buy 1,010.5 acres of land in Selangor state for 330.1
million ringgit ($110 million), it said in a statement. The
company plans a property project with potential sales of 3.5
billion ringgit on the land, it said. The shares rose 4.1
percent to 3.85 ringgit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
